WEBVTT

00:00.100 --> 00:00.902
<i>Previously on "Castle"...</i>

00:01.905 --> 00:03.007
Ask me why I'm here.

00:03.017 --> 00:04.917
You know, I ask myself
that question every day.

00:05.127 --> 00:07.028
That was Paula, my Agent,
with big news

00:07.029 --> 00:09.064
about my book, "Heat Wave."

00:09.074 --> 00:10.674
Are they really making
a Nikki Heat movie?

00:10.864 --> 00:12.366
Dude, did I call it or what?

00:12.376 --> 00:13.866
And you are
about to be immortalized

00:13.867 --> 00:15.101
on the silver screen.

00:15.206 --> 00:17.308
(Man) Yeah, I'd like to report
a murder. I did it.

00:17.370 --> 00:20.739
He called to report his crime.
It's like he did this for fun.
(Camera shutter clicks)

00:20.740 --> 00:23.642
Nikki Heat. He dedicated
this murder to me.

00:23.776 --> 00:26.277
Nikki Heat I presume.
It's Beckett.

00:26.312 --> 00:29.347
Special Agent Jordan Shaw.
Tell me everything you know
about Jordan Shaw.

00:29.381 --> 00:30.616
She is like the federal you.

00:30.626 --> 00:33.426
(Shaw) If our killer is obsessed with
Nikki Heat, Then so are we.

00:33.450 --> 00:34.649
So how long have you two
been sleeping together?

00:34.684 --> 00:38.079
Excuse me?
I <i>am not</i> going to leave you alone.

00:38.113 --> 00:41.325
Why don't you two escort
the body to the morgue?

00:41.360 --> 00:43.033
Once you're dressed,
of course.

00:43.068 --> 00:44.715
(Lanie) "b-u-r"--

00:44.749 --> 00:46.493
"burn."
Nikki will burn.

00:46.528 --> 00:48.537
Somebody always
has to die, Nikki.

00:48.547 --> 00:50.547
(Castle) If the man in the window...
(gunshot) was Ben Conrad

00:50.572 --> 00:51.812
he would've
shot himself on the left side.

00:52.036 --> 00:55.109
Ben's not our killer.
Beckett.
(cell phone rings)

00:55.143 --> 00:57.146
(beeps)
What, Castle?

00:58.493 --> 01:00.497
It wasn't Ben Conrad.
He's not the killer!

01:00.531 --> 01:03.803
The killer's still alive!
The killer's still alive!

01:03.838 --> 01:06.207
<i>(male voice) Good-bye, Nikki.</i>

01:06.242 --> 01:08.944
<i>Good-bye, Nikki.</i>

01:08.979 --> 01:12.250
(debris clatters)

01:19.593 --> 01:21.894
(Castle)
Kate, are you in there?!

01:21.929 --> 01:23.330
(bangs on door)
Kate!

01:23.365 --> 01:25.301
(bangs)

01:25.335 --> 01:26.703
Ouch.

01:26.737 --> 01:28.610
Ow! (grunts)

01:29.387 --> 01:31.155
Kate?

01:31.189 --> 01:33.592
Kate!

01:33.626 --> 01:36.427
(debris clattering)

01:36.462 --> 01:39.764
(coughing)

01:39.798 --> 01:42.936
Kate?

01:42.970 --> 01:46.475
(coughing)

01:46.510 --> 01:48.178
Kate.

01:48.212 --> 01:49.380
(coughing continues)

01:49.414 --> 01:51.383
You're alive.

01:51.417 --> 01:52.918
Whoa. And you're naked.

01:52.952 --> 01:54.420
Castle, turn around!

01:54.454 --> 01:55.822
(coughs)

01:55.856 --> 01:58.426
You know, your apartment
<i>is</i> on fire.

01:58.460 --> 02:00.963
Now might not be
the best time for modesty.

02:00.997 --> 02:03.533
Castle, hand me a towel.

02:03.567 --> 02:06.002
Your towels are on fire.
Well, what about the bathrobe?

02:06.037 --> 02:09.440
The... do you have anything
to wear that's nonflammable?

02:09.473 --> 02:11.709
Castle.
Sorry.

02:11.743 --> 02:13.645
Give me your jacket.

02:13.679 --> 02:15.147
(whispers) Okay, okay.

02:15.181 --> 02:17.415
Don't look.
(normal voice) I'm not.

02:17.449 --> 02:19.484
Don't look.
I'm no-not looking.

02:19.518 --> 02:21.654
Okay.

02:23.023 --> 02:25.593
All right?
Yeah.

02:25.627 --> 02:26.661
Okay.

02:26.695 --> 02:30.733
I dove into the tub
just as it blew.

02:30.767 --> 02:32.135
Yeah, can you walk?

02:32.169 --> 02:35.436
Ugh. Yeah, just...
A little banged up.

02:35.470 --> 02:37.637
Okay. Come on.
Nice and easy.

02:37.672 --> 02:39.706
Yeah.
Nice and easy.

02:39.740 --> 02:41.675
(grunts)
Are you in any pain?

02:41.709 --> 02:44.077
Well, not nearly
as much as you.
(sirens wailing)

02:44.112 --> 02:47.114
It's killing you, isn't it?
What?

02:47.149 --> 02:49.851
(wailing continues)
Having to wait this long
to tell me

02:49.885 --> 02:52.921
how you banged down the door.
You want me to start from the beginning?

02:52.956 --> 02:54.991
(helicopter blades whirring)

02:55.025 --> 02:58.295
(sirens wailing)

02:58.329 --> 02:59.963
FBI.
Right over there.

02:59.998 --> 03:01.966
(police radio chatter)

03:02.000 --> 03:04.001
Beckett. How you doing?

03:04.035 --> 03:06.634
Yeah, I'm fine.
What'd you see when you came home?

03:06.669 --> 03:08.736
The, uh, the doors were locked
like I left them,

03:08.771 --> 03:11.640
the windows were shut
and... I don't know.

03:11.674 --> 03:14.610
Nothing seemed out of place.
But I don't know,

03:14.644 --> 03:16.313
You know, 'cause I thought
the case was done.

03:16.323 --> 03:17.943
It's not, but you are.

03:19.357 --> 03:20.390
What?

03:20.423 --> 03:22.657
Till we find the right guy.

03:22.692 --> 03:24.792
Wait.
This is my apartment.

03:24.827 --> 03:27.928
Okay?
My life and my case.

03:27.962 --> 03:29.429
Okay, fine.

03:29.463 --> 03:31.362
My rules.

03:31.397 --> 03:33.696
You do what I say
when I say

03:33.731 --> 03:35.464
and how I say it.

03:35.499 --> 03:38.034
And there will be a security
detail on you at all times.

03:38.068 --> 03:39.535
Fine.
Good.

03:39.570 --> 03:42.571
Fire's out. You can
head up now if you want.

03:42.606 --> 03:45.574
(siren wails)

03:45.608 --> 03:48.878
(camera shutter clicking)
(man) ...Consistent with that pattern.

03:48.912 --> 03:51.114
(siren wailing)

03:51.148 --> 03:53.816
(man) checking for
secondary devices right now.

03:53.850 --> 03:55.017
(police radio chatter)

03:55.972 --> 03:58.006
Did anybody find
my father's watch?

03:58.040 --> 04:01.609
It's not in the hall.
The damage isn't as bad
in your bedroom.

04:01.644 --> 04:04.144
But your clothes do smell
like smoke and explosives.

04:04.179 --> 04:05.880
Does anyone know if insurance
pays for dry cleaning?

04:05.987 --> 04:08.455
I've got the blast seat here.
(camera shutter clicks)

04:08.489 --> 04:10.290
Well, it had to have been
a small device,

04:10.325 --> 04:11.360
otherwise I would've seen it.

04:11.470 --> 04:13.570
The lab will have
the breakdown by morning,

04:13.895 --> 04:15.795
but that's cyclonite.

04:15.829 --> 04:18.430
Same thing we found
in Ben Conrad's apartment.

04:18.464 --> 04:19.798
So what tipped you?

04:19.833 --> 04:23.036
It wasn't me. It was Castle.

04:23.070 --> 04:25.004
Uh, well, our supposed killer,
Ben Conrad,

04:25.039 --> 04:26.739
shot himself
with his right hand,

04:26.774 --> 04:28.341
Yet the man that
Detective Beckett and I

04:28.376 --> 04:31.510
saw in the window was holding
the gun in his left hand.

04:31.544 --> 04:34.278
The shot went off just as soon
as he stepped out of view.

04:34.313 --> 04:35.413
He wouldn't have--
couldn't have--had time

04:35.448 --> 04:37.048
to switch hands that fast.

04:37.169 --> 04:39.635
Our real killer shot Ben Conrad,
placed the gun in his hand,

04:39.670 --> 04:41.103
making it look like a suicide.

04:41.113 --> 04:42.337
We were outside the door.
We heard the shot.

04:42.338 --> 04:44.638
<i>Go!</i>
<i>(agents) FBI!</i>

04:44.672 --> 04:46.839
There's no way else
out of that apartment.

04:46.873 --> 04:48.507
So if Ben Conrad
didn't kill himself...

04:48.517 --> 04:50.917
then our killer was in
the apartment the whole time.

04:51.179 --> 04:52.281
How the hell
did we miss him?

04:52.291 --> 04:54.391
(Castle) Let's go find out.

04:56.583 --> 04:59.685
(knocking on walls)

05:05.291 --> 05:07.591
You guys.

05:07.625 --> 05:10.160
Take a look in here.

05:11.320 --> 05:12.422
I think I found something.

05:12.910 --> 05:14.843
(Castle)
What have you got?

05:14.878 --> 05:17.578
(grunts)
Maybe his hiding place.

05:25.517 --> 05:27.183
Whoa.

05:27.218 --> 05:28.951
Discarded clothing.

05:28.986 --> 05:31.987
(Shaw)
The exact same outfit

05:32.021 --> 05:34.455
Conrad was wearing
when we found him.

05:34.490 --> 05:36.991
(Beckett) Right down to
a fake beard to match Conrad's.

05:37.025 --> 05:39.827
The killer wanted us
to think he <i>was</i> Conrad.

05:39.861 --> 05:42.829
That's why the man
that I saw in the window,

05:42.863 --> 05:44.764
the one from
our eyewitness accounts,

05:44.798 --> 05:47.366
led us straight to Ben.
Which means the real Ben Conrad

05:47.400 --> 05:49.834
was being held hostage
in his own apartment

05:49.868 --> 05:51.702
the entire case.

05:51.736 --> 05:54.304
He must have been
bound and duct-taped,

05:54.338 --> 05:57.573
with no idea that he was
being blamed for three murders.

05:57.607 --> 05:59.574
Each of our victims
was carefully selected

05:59.642 --> 06:01.742
for their connection
to Ben Conrad,

06:01.777 --> 06:03.610
making him
the perfect patsy.

06:03.645 --> 06:05.011
The killer's a chameleon,

06:05.046 --> 06:08.014
changing his identity
to get close to the victims.

06:08.048 --> 06:10.582
He becomes Ben Conrad,
he becomes invisible.

06:10.617 --> 06:12.583
Nobody's looking for him.
And then we come here,

06:12.618 --> 06:15.053
and we find exactly
what we expect to find--

06:15.087 --> 06:17.355
our suspect dead on the ground--
case closed.

06:17.389 --> 06:19.456
Meanwhile, our killer
was right here,

06:19.490 --> 06:21.124
hidden in this secret room.

06:21.158 --> 06:23.193
He was here the whole time,
and we missed him.

06:23.289 --> 06:24.688
(cell phone ringing)

06:24.723 --> 06:26.723
(Shaw) I'll get
the evidence team down here,

06:26.757 --> 06:28.658
see what they can find.
Beckett.

06:28.692 --> 06:31.493
(man)
You are supposed to be dead.

06:32.253 --> 06:34.688
I'm sorry
to disappoint you.

06:34.723 --> 06:35.791
It was supposed to be over,
Nikki.

06:36.040 --> 06:37.907
It was supposed to be done.

06:37.942 --> 06:40.742
But now... now I have to keep going.
(woman) No! <i>No!</i>

06:40.777 --> 06:43.845
(three gunshots)

06:43.879 --> 06:46.881
<font color=#7FFF00>♪ Castle 2x18 ♪</font>
<font color=#FFFF00>Boom</font>
Original Air Date on March 29, 2010

06:46.915 --> 06:49.983
-- Sync, corrected by <font color=#00FF00>elderman</font> --
-- for <font color=#00FFFF>www.addic7ed.com</font> --

06:53.995 --> 06:55.429
He used her cell phone

06:55.463 --> 06:57.731
and then he left it on
so we could trace it.

06:57.828 --> 06:59.361
Gloria Rodriguez.

06:59.396 --> 07:02.162
This is her I.D. badge
from a hotel in Midtown.

07:02.197 --> 07:04.066
Probably on her way home
from work.

07:04.076 --> 07:05.296
Huh. Found a slug.

07:06.607 --> 07:08.007
Letter etching?

07:08.042 --> 07:10.843
(police radio chatter)
No, it looks clean.

07:10.877 --> 07:13.512
The other murders
were planned.

07:13.546 --> 07:15.546
This one
was done out of anger,

07:15.580 --> 07:18.783
wanting to be in control.
All because I lived.

07:18.817 --> 07:21.885
You can't blame yourself
for that.

07:21.919 --> 07:24.620
How did he know you lived?

07:24.654 --> 07:26.454
(police radio chatter)

07:26.488 --> 07:27.621
He was watching...

07:29.134 --> 07:30.269
at the aftermath.

07:30.401 --> 07:31.968
Everything about
this guy's profile

07:32.003 --> 07:34.903
tells me he was watching
at the other crime scenes.

07:34.938 --> 07:38.073
Yeah, but the first thing we did
was compare crime scene photos.

07:38.108 --> 07:40.342
Yeah, I know. We ran them
through facial recognition.

07:40.376 --> 07:42.311
But he was there.
I know he was there.

07:42.321 --> 07:43.921
He wouldn't be in the crowd.

07:44.045 --> 07:45.246
He'd know
that's where we'd look.

07:45.405 --> 07:48.773
(sirens wailing)
No, he hides in plain sight.
He's a chameleon.

07:48.808 --> 07:50.842
We didn't see him
in the crowd...

07:50.876 --> 07:53.544
because he was dressed
as one of us.

07:53.578 --> 07:55.445
(Shaw)
Same cop, 30 photos,

07:55.480 --> 07:58.515
not one of them has
a clear shot of his face.

07:58.549 --> 08:00.750
That is not a coincidence.

08:00.784 --> 08:02.685
He knew
where the camera was.

08:02.695 --> 08:04.215
He knows our playbook.

08:04.302 --> 08:06.403
I'm gonna get Ryan and Esposito
to canvass the other uniforms.

08:06.625 --> 08:07.693
Maybe they can get
a description.

08:07.703 --> 08:09.203
Not that it'll do any good.

08:10.400 --> 08:12.402
The last sketch we got of this guy,
He looked like Ben Conrad.

08:12.436 --> 08:15.171
Okay, do you have
a better idea?

08:15.205 --> 08:17.673
'cause I am all out.

08:17.707 --> 08:19.476
And if we don't catch him soon,
he's gonna kill again.

08:19.486 --> 08:20.786
You can't
take this personally.

08:20.936 --> 08:23.437
The hell I can't.
He just blew up my apartment.

08:23.471 --> 08:25.738
I think
that's pretty damn personal.

08:25.773 --> 08:27.441
Do you know how
they caught son of Sam?

08:28.427 --> 08:29.647
A p-parking ticket.

08:29.653 --> 08:31.121
Berkowitz parked too close
to a fire hydrant.

08:31.512 --> 08:33.979
All we need to find
is our parking ticket,

08:34.014 --> 08:35.981
and we catch
this son of a bitch.

08:36.015 --> 08:39.551
As smart as he is, he's got
a fatal flaw--hubris.

08:39.585 --> 08:42.720
It's not enough for him to be
smart. He wants us to know it.

08:42.755 --> 08:44.322
He wants us to <i>know</i>
he fooled us.

08:44.869 --> 08:46.736
All of his first victims...

08:46.770 --> 08:48.671
the personal injury lawyer,

08:48.705 --> 08:51.607
the dog Walker,
the taxidermist,

08:51.641 --> 08:56.511
they all link back to the death
of Ben Conrad's dog.

08:56.545 --> 08:58.279
How could our killer

08:58.313 --> 09:01.281
have known all the players
in someone else's life?

09:01.316 --> 09:02.583
He must have known
Ben Conrad.

09:03.139 --> 09:04.939
So that's where we start.

09:04.973 --> 09:06.374
We treat Ben Conrad

09:06.408 --> 09:08.375
as the first victim
in this case.

09:08.410 --> 09:11.278
And then we find out where
he intersected with our killer.

09:11.312 --> 09:14.147
<i>(man) The exact cause</i>
<i>of last night's explosion</i>

09:14.181 --> 09:15.881
<i>in Greenwich Village...</i>
Dad!

09:15.916 --> 09:18.485
Hey. Hey. Oh! Hey.
Aw, I'm all right.

09:18.518 --> 09:20.950
I'm all right.
Where's Detective Beckett?

09:20.984 --> 09:22.451
At the precinct.

09:22.485 --> 09:25.554
(exhales) I can't imagine
how she survived that explosion.

09:25.588 --> 09:27.555
Where was she
when it went off?

09:27.590 --> 09:30.558
She was there. She, uh...
jumped into the bathtub.

09:30.592 --> 09:32.626
The bathroom door
and the cast-iron tub

09:32.661 --> 09:34.630
protected her from the blast.
Oh! (blows air)

09:34.665 --> 09:37.699
Dad, why is that person
going after Detective Beckett?

09:37.733 --> 09:40.235
Well, at the moment,
all we have is a theory.

09:40.269 --> 09:42.837
But--but we know more now,
and we have a strategy.

09:42.871 --> 09:44.771
Do you think
he'll come after you?

09:44.806 --> 09:46.840
Oh, sweetheart.
I'm gonna be fine.

09:46.874 --> 09:48.577
You are stuck with me
for a long, long time.

09:48.587 --> 09:49.587
You know, I'm supposed to
move out today.

09:49.784 --> 09:52.018
I think I should stay here with Alexis.
Well, there's no need.

09:52.215 --> 09:54.582
Montgomery has someone keeping
an eagle eye on our building.

09:54.617 --> 09:57.051
But all the same,
we should be on the alert.

09:58.506 --> 10:00.540
(sniffs)
I need to go change...

10:00.575 --> 10:03.643
(grunts)
and go back and help.

10:03.677 --> 10:05.544
See?

10:05.579 --> 10:07.512
He's okay.

10:07.547 --> 10:09.514
(man) No, I appreciate
the information.

10:09.548 --> 10:10.882
Hey.

10:10.916 --> 10:12.384
Hey.

10:12.418 --> 10:14.453
Where is everybody?

10:14.488 --> 10:17.855
Ryan and Esposito
are talking to Conrad's sister,

10:17.890 --> 10:21.291
and... Agent Shaw
is briefing the mayor.

10:21.326 --> 10:24.227
Oh. I'm sure he'll be
less than thrilled

10:24.261 --> 10:26.862
to learn that Conrad
is just another victim.
Hmm.

10:26.896 --> 10:28.263
Nothing like the threat

10:28.297 --> 10:30.264
of being murdered
by a serial killer to stifle tourism.

10:30.298 --> 10:32.367
Yeah, and it doesn't help
that everyone in the city

10:32.401 --> 10:34.436
thinks that
we caught the guy.

10:34.470 --> 10:36.704
Speaking of Ben Conrad,
what have you found out?

10:36.738 --> 10:39.373
34 years old,
never married--

10:39.407 --> 10:41.874
I'm going out
on a limb here saying,

10:41.909 --> 10:44.510
judging from his relationship
with his dog, Mr. Bumpkins,

10:44.544 --> 10:46.578
he didn't have a girlfriend.
Yeah, well, other than the people

10:46.613 --> 10:48.981
that we've already run down
from the dog park,

10:49.015 --> 10:51.583
he doesn't even have friends.
The man stuffed his dog.

10:51.617 --> 10:54.886
Well, Conrad's sister
confirms that he was a loner.

10:54.920 --> 10:57.587
Told her that when he lost
his job a couple of months ago

10:57.622 --> 11:00.024
that he spent his days
e-mailing résumés

11:00.058 --> 11:02.526
at coffee shops that offer free internet.
And other than Bumpkins,

11:02.560 --> 11:04.661
his only other joy in life
was the Knicks.
Poor guy.

11:04.695 --> 11:06.729
Jordan said
the profile indicated that

11:06.764 --> 11:09.531
the killer hunted Conrad.
If he wasn't a friend,

11:09.566 --> 11:11.034
then he must have
met up with him somewhere

11:11.068 --> 11:12.703
where people strike up
a casual conversation.

11:12.713 --> 11:13.713
We figure if he camped out

11:13.899 --> 11:15.734
with his laptop
at a coffee shop, our killer

11:15.817 --> 11:18.116
could've sat down next to him,
and they got to talking.

11:18.126 --> 11:19.826
His sister said
that he was a Knicks fan?

11:21.226 --> 11:23.494
What's missing
from these pictures?

11:23.528 --> 11:24.662
Good taste.
Area rug.

11:24.823 --> 11:25.690
(Ryan) Decent lighting.

11:25.827 --> 11:28.761
A TV, which means he would
have to walk to a local bar

11:28.796 --> 11:31.197
in order to watch the games.
Yeah, if you're a Knicks fan,

11:31.231 --> 11:33.366
you gotta share your pain
with somebody.
True.

11:33.401 --> 11:35.535
Okay, you two
take all of the coffee shops

11:35.569 --> 11:37.403
within a 5-block radius
of Conrad's apartment.

11:37.437 --> 11:39.504
See if anyone remembers him
talking to a customer.

11:39.539 --> 11:42.440
Castle and I will take the bars.
And if you keep quoting Jordan,

11:42.475 --> 11:45.676
I am going to turn the radio <i>way</i> up.
(singsongy) Jealous.

11:45.710 --> 11:47.010
(snickers)

11:47.045 --> 11:50.447
<i>(the genders)</i>
<i>♪ and I said, hey, baby ♪</i>

11:52.392 --> 11:54.193
You know, pub crawls
are supposed to greet you

11:54.301 --> 11:55.767
with a smile
and a shot of jager,

11:55.843 --> 11:58.578
not, "no, we've never seen
the guy before. Keep moving."

11:58.612 --> 12:00.612
This is beginning
to feel pointless.

12:00.647 --> 12:02.147
Buck up, Castle.

12:02.182 --> 12:04.015
I got a feeling
this place is different.

12:04.050 --> 12:05.517
<i>♪ let's pretend ♪</i>

12:05.551 --> 12:07.552
<i>♪ let's pretend ♪</i>

12:07.586 --> 12:09.686
(Beckett) It's still
an ongoing investigation.

12:09.720 --> 12:13.054
So we're gonna need you
to take that banner down.

12:13.088 --> 12:15.056
I was just trying
to work an angle.

12:15.090 --> 12:17.024
You should understand
what it's like

12:17.058 --> 12:19.159
being a woman
in a man's world.

12:19.193 --> 12:22.729
Uh, did Ben Conrad
ever talk to you

12:22.763 --> 12:25.131
about the recent death of his dog?
Sure.

12:25.166 --> 12:27.933
He loved to flap his gums to me
about that little dropkick.

12:27.968 --> 12:30.602
One time, he cried.
Well, what about  the other customers,

12:30.637 --> 12:33.872
he ever talk to them?
He mostly drank alone and watched the games.

12:33.906 --> 12:35.340
Though a couple of weeks ago,

12:35.374 --> 12:37.708
he did strike it up with some guy.
Can you describe him?

12:37.742 --> 12:40.310
Average looking, a bit off,
like Conrad.

12:40.344 --> 12:42.779
They sat at that high top
over there.

12:42.813 --> 12:44.814
I figured,
hey, birds of a feather.

12:44.848 --> 12:48.417
This other guy, did he
ever pay with a edit card?

12:48.451 --> 12:50.885
The only time he ever said
two words to me

12:50.919 --> 12:52.453
was the other week when
he asked me to call him a cab.

12:52.463 --> 12:53.483
Do you remember when?

12:53.588 --> 12:56.089
I remember exactly when--
the Knicks were in overtime,

12:56.123 --> 12:59.392
and I missed the end
while I was on hold.
Thanks.

12:59.426 --> 13:01.893
Cab company said
that they sent a taxi there

13:01.928 --> 13:04.463
10:45, the night
of the Knicks game.

13:04.497 --> 13:05.365
You got the drop-off point?

13:05.523 --> 13:07.557
Yeah. West village, corner
of Varick and Downing.

13:08.994 --> 13:11.429
Home?
You know, I bet about 50,000 people

13:11.463 --> 13:13.196
live within walking distance
of that corner.

13:13.231 --> 13:14.864
We could canvass
local businesses.

13:14.898 --> 13:16.865
For an average-looking
white guy?

13:16.900 --> 13:19.969
I mean, we can't even be sure
what he looks like.

13:20.004 --> 13:21.505
Looks aren't
the only methods we have

13:21.639 --> 13:24.239
to identify him.
We also have behavior.

13:24.274 --> 13:27.408
You think you can idenfy
him through behavior?

13:27.443 --> 13:29.576
Well, originally, his behavior
seemed inconsistent,

13:29.610 --> 13:32.545
but that was because he was
pretending to be someone else.

13:32.579 --> 13:34.280
We know a lot more now.

13:34.314 --> 13:36.783
He is a show-off,

13:36.817 --> 13:38.985
a game player with
an exceptionally high I.Q.

13:39.019 --> 13:41.753
but it's not enough
to be smart.

13:41.788 --> 13:45.123
He also has a pathological need
to validate it,

13:45.157 --> 13:48.492
which tells me that he probably
belongs to an organization

13:48.527 --> 13:51.428
like Mensa or Prometheus.

13:51.463 --> 13:53.296
He is a chameleon.

13:53.331 --> 13:54.731
So we can assume

13:54.765 --> 13:57.266
that he is living under
a stolen identity.

13:57.301 --> 13:59.201
And he is. Literate.

13:59.236 --> 14:02.237
He has already shown
certain dispositions

14:02.271 --> 14:05.239
in his fascination
with Nikki Heat.

14:05.274 --> 14:08.542
So we've drawn up a list
of periodicals and magazines

14:08.577 --> 14:11.178
that he likely subscribes to.

14:11.212 --> 14:12.779
I get half of these.

14:12.813 --> 14:15.848
Yes, and you also
kill people for a living.

14:15.882 --> 14:17.516
In your books.

14:17.550 --> 14:19.518
This is a pretty wide net.

14:19.552 --> 14:21.453
So is Varick and Downing

14:21.487 --> 14:25.423
And so are memberships
in high-I.Q. societies.

14:25.457 --> 14:29.159
But put them all together,
and sometimes we get lucky.

14:29.194 --> 14:32.795
You mean like Berkowitz's parking ticket?
Oh, it's not always that neat.

14:32.830 --> 14:35.364
You just keep adding
pieces of the puzzle

14:35.399 --> 14:36.732
until a picture emerges.

14:36.766 --> 14:38.433
(Avery) We collated
subscription information

14:38.468 --> 14:39.868
from the profiled periodicals

14:39.902 --> 14:42.904
as well as member lists from
the high-I.Q. organizations

14:42.939 --> 14:45.838
within a 1-mile radius
of the Varick and Downing area.

14:45.873 --> 14:48.174
(computer beeps)
We got 17 hits.

14:48.208 --> 14:50.175
Run the names
through our database.

14:50.210 --> 14:52.244
Most serials have
some kind of indication

14:52.278 --> 14:53.379
Of violent behavior--

14:53.489 --> 14:56.190
Criminal or psychiatric records.
(beep)

14:56.224 --> 15:00.826
Negative for any matches.
All right. Well, at least
we gave it a shot.

15:01.215 --> 15:03.883
I'll have our teams interview these guys--
"huh" what?  Huh.

15:04.321 --> 15:05.822
This one here--
Chris Doherty.

15:05.856 --> 15:07.824
We've got
a recent driver's license,

15:07.858 --> 15:10.359
But according to
his social security number,

15:10.393 --> 15:13.627
Chris Doherty died
six years ago.

15:13.661 --> 15:16.162
His living
under a stolen identity.

15:17.840 --> 15:20.413
(Shaw) So does it say where
our dead guy supposedly lived?

15:23.380 --> 15:25.581
(Avery) his address
puts him half a block

15:25.616 --> 15:28.750
From Downing and Varick.
Okay. Now I'm officially impressed.

15:28.785 --> 15:31.719
Don't be.
Not until he's in our custody.

15:31.754 --> 15:33.888
Let's roll.

15:40.763 --> 15:41.796
(whirs)

15:41.864 --> 15:44.199
(crash)
(man) Go! Go! Go!

15:47.670 --> 15:50.104
(man) Bathroom's clear.
(man) Bedroom's clear.

15:50.138 --> 15:52.305
All clear.

